#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: stop the country edge-glow from bleeding into the ocean.

Mike's report: "isolate the border colors so that they only fill within the
borders of that country, don't have them bleed into the ocean etc" - live-
confirmed the whole Atlantic/Gulf seaboard, Cuba, and other coastlines showed
a visible colored haze in the water, worst at low/world-view zoom.

Root cause: country-glow-soft/tight are line layers with a FLAT (zoom-
independent) line-width/line-blur in screen pixels - 18px/10blur and 7px/2.2
blur. A line straddles its source geometry (the country border) evenly on
both sides, so roughly half that width always bleeds past the coastline into
open water, same as it bleeds onto a neighboring country (which is the
intended "relief map" look Mike asked for originally - this fix targets
specifically the ocean side, not neighbor-to-neighbor blending).
Screen-pixel width means the same 18px covers a WILDLY different amount of
real distance depending on zoom: live-measured 18px = ~4.6 degrees of
longitude at the default world-view zoom (1.45), but a small fraction of a
degree once zoomed into a single country. That's why the bleed looked worst
at the very view most people land on first.

Two-part fix, verified live in combination before shipping:
1. Made line-width/line-blur zoom-responsive (thin/subtle at world view,
   ramping up to the current bold thickness by zoom 5, where 18px is already
   a small, reasonable fraction of what's on screen) - directly shrinks the
   worst-case bleed instead of just papering over it.
2. Added a precomputed "sea collar" - the real ocean, minus a 1-degree-
   buffered copy of every country's land, i.e. a sea-only band hugging every
   coastline - painted in the ocean's own color (#0a1b30) directly on top of
   the glow layers (after country-glow-tight, before the crisp "borders"
   line), so any residual bleed that still reaches open water gets covered
   cleanly. Computed via shapely (buffer + difference on the unioned MAPDATA
   land polygons), simplified for size. Does NOT touch neighbor-to-neighbor
   glow bleed at all (that mask only exists over open ocean, never over any
   country's own land), so the original relief-map look between adjacent
   countries is unchanged.
Both pieces tested together live (temporary rectangular test mask over the
Gulf of Mexico) at both zoom 4.2 and the default 1.45 - confirmed clean,
bleed-free coastline inside the tested area at both zooms, with the
untested-area bleed for comparison still visible outside it.

Same _isCountriesRef visibility toggle as the glow layers themselves - the
collar only ever shows when the Countries reference layer is active.

Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_seacollar_fix.py index.html index.html
"""
